<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;I think if you buy from people who are taking care of the land,&#8221; Alice Waters says, &#8220;you&#8217;re supporting the future of this country.&#8221; The chef activist speaks to Doug Aitken in Berkeley, Calif., at an <a href="//edibleschoolyard.org">Edible Schoolyard</a>, her project to educate students about agriculture, economy and the environment. The interview is part of <a title="The Source" href="//dougaitkenthesource.com/">the Source</a>, a series of candid video conversations with several dozen noteworthy figures about their creative processes, currently on view in a custom pavilion at the <a title="Sundance Film Festival" href="//www.sundance.org/festival/">Sundance Film Festival</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">T is exclusively presenting clips of nine of Aitkenâs conversations for the series â with Waters, Aaron Koblin, Theaster Gates, Liz Diller, Tilda Swinton, Paolo Soleri, James Turrell, Liz Glynn and Beck. To see them, visit our <a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/t-magazine/source-doug-aitken.html">project page</a> for the Source, where we will be rolling out the videos one at a time over a two-week span.</p>
    </div>
